# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tcp-congestion-control
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Some communications equipment manufacturers designed unnecessarily large buffers into some of their network products.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] In such equipment, bufferbloat occurs when a network link becomes congested, causing packets to become queued for long periods in these oversized buffers.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] In a first-in first-out queuing system, overly large buffers result in longer queues and higher latency, and do not improve network throughput.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] It can also be induced by specific slow-speed connections hindering the on-time delivery of other packets.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The bufferbloat phenomenon was described as early as 1985.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] It gained more widespread attention starting in 2009.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] According to some sources, the most frequent cause of high latency ("lag") in online video games is local home network bufferbloat.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] High latency can render modern online gaming impossible.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] An established rule of thumb for the network equipment manufacturers was to provide buffers large enough to accommodate at least 250 ms of buffering for a stream of traffic passing through a device.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] For example, a router's Gigabit Ethernet interface would require a relatively large 32 MB buffer.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Such sizing of the buffers can lead to failure of the TCP congestion control algorithm.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The buffers then take some time to drain, before congestion control resets and the TCP connection ramps back up to speed and fills the buffers again.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Bufferbloat thus causes problems such as high and variable latency, and choking network bottlenecks for all other flows as the buffer becomes full of the packets of one TCP stream and other packets are then dropped.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] A bloated buffer has an effect only when this buffer is actually used.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] In other words, oversized buffers have a damaging effect only when the link they buffer becomes a bottleneck.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The size of the buffer serving a bottleneck can be measured using the ping utility provided by most operating systems.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] First, the other host should be pinged continuously; then, a several-second-long download from it should be started and stopped a few times.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] By design, the TCP congestion avoidance algorithm will rapidly fill up the bottleneck on the route.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] If downloading (and uploading, respectively) correlates with a direct and important increase in the round-trip time reported by ping, then it demonstrates that the buffer of the current bottleneck in the download (and upload, respectively) direction is bloated.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Since the increase in the round-trip time is caused by the buffer on the bottleneck, the maximum increase gives a rough estimation of its size in milliseconds.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] In the previous example, using an advanced traceroute tool instead of the simple pinging (for example, MTR) will not only demonstrate the existence of a bloated buffer on the bottleneck, but will also pinpoint its location in the network.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Traceroute achieves this by displaying the route (path) and measuring transit delays of packets across the network.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The history of the route is recorded as round-trip times of the packets received from each successive host (remote node) in the route (path).
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Most TCP congestion control algorithms rely on measuring the occurrence of packet drops to determine the available bandwidth between two ends of a connection.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The algorithms speed up the data transfer until packets start to drop, then slow down the transmission rate.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Ideally, they keep adjusting the transmission rate until it reaches an equilibrium speed of the link.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] So that the algorithms can select a suitable transfer speed, the feedback about packet drops must occur in a timely manner.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] With a large buffer that has been filled, the packets will arrive at their destination, but with a higher latency.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The packets were not dropped, so TCP does not slow down once the uplink has been saturated, further filling the buffer.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Newly arriving packets are dropped only when the buffer is fully saturated.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Once this happens, TCP may even decide that the path of the connection has changed, and again go into the more aggressive search for a new operating point.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Packets are queued within a network buffer before being transmitted; in problematic situations, packets are dropped only if the buffer is full.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] On older routers, buffers were fairly small, so they filled quickly, and therefore packets began to drop shortly after the link became saturated, so the TCP protocol could adjust, and the issue would not become apparent.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] On newer routers, buffers have become large enough to hold several seconds of buffered data.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] To TCP, a congested link can appear to be operating normally as the buffer fills.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The TCP algorithm is unaware that the link is congested and does not start to take corrective action until the buffer finally overflows and packets are dropped.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] All packets passing through a simple buffer implemented as a single queue will experience similar delay, so the latency of any connection that passes through a filled buffer will be affected.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Available channel bandwidth can also end up being unused, as some fast destinations may not be promptly reached due to buffers clogged with data awaiting delivery to slow destinations.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] These effects impair the interactivity of applications using other network protocols, including UDP used in latency-sensitive applications like VoIP and online gaming.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Regardless of bandwidth requirements, any type of service that requires consistently low latency or jitter-free transmission can be affected by bufferbloat.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Such services include digital voice calls (VOIP), online gaming, video chat, and other interactive applications such as radio streaming, video on demand, and remote login.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] When the bufferbloat phenomenon is present and the network is under load, even normal web page loads can take many seconds to complete, or simple DNS queries can fail due to timeouts.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Actually any TCP connection can timeout and disconnect, and UDP packets can get discarded.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Since the continuation of a TCP download stream depends on acknowledgement (ACK) packets in the upload stream, a bufferbloat problem in the upload can cause failure of other non-related download applications, because the client ACK packets do not timely reach the internet server.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The DSLReports Speedtest was an easy-to-use test that included a score for bufferbloat.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The DSLReports site went fully offline on March 26, 2025.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The ICSI Netalyzr was another on-line tool that could be used for checking networks for the presence of bufferbloat, together with checking for many other common configuration problems.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The service was shut down in March 2019.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] In the absence of DSLReports and Netalyzr, current browser-based bufferbloat tests include the Waveform Bufferbloat Test and Y2KDASH, which samples loaded latency continuously rather than in a single-shot test.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The bufferbloat.net web site lists tools and procedures for determining whether a connection has excess buffering that will slow it down.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Several technical solutions exist which can be broadly grouped into two categories: solutions that target the network and solutions that target the endpoints.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The two types of solutions are often complementary.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The problem sometimes arrives with a combination of fast and slow network paths.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Network solutions generally take the form of queue management algorithms.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] This type of solution has been the focus of the IETF AQM working group.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] The problem may also be mitigated by reducing the buffer size on the OS and network hardware; however, this is often not configurable, and optimal buffer size is dependent on line rate, which may differ for different destinations.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] Utilizing DiffServ (and employing multiple priority-based queues) helps in prioritizing transmission of low-latency traffic (such as VoIP, videoconferencing, gaming), relegating dealing with congestion and bufferbloat onto non-prioritized traffic.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] For the longest delay TCP connections to still get their fair share of the bandwidth, the buffer size should be at least the bandwidth-delay product divided by the square root of the number of simultaneous streams.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/bufferbloat] A typical rule of thumb is 50 ms of line rate data, but some popular consumer grade switches only have 1 ms, which may result in extra bandwidth loss on the longer delay connections in case of local contention with others.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] In 2006, the first CUBIC implementation was released in Linux kernel 2.6.13.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] Since kernel version 2.6.19, CUBIC replaces BIC-TCP as the default TCP congestion control algorithm in the Linux kernel.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] MacOS adopted TCP CUBIC with the OS X Yosemite release in 2014, while the previous release OS X Mavericks still used TCP New Reno.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] Microsoft adopted it by default in Windows 10.1709 Fall Creators Update (2017), and Windows Server 2016 1709 update.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] CUBIC is a less aggressive and more systematic derivative of BIC TCP, in which the window size is a cubic function of time since the last congestion event, with the inflection point set to the window size prior to the event.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] Because it is a cubic function, there are two components to window growth.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] The first is a concave portion where the window size quickly ramps up to the size before the last congestion event.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] Next is the convex growth where CUBIC probes for more bandwidth, slowly at first then very rapidly.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] CUBIC spends a lot of time at a plateau between the concave and convex growth region which allows the network to stabilize before CUBIC begins looking for more bandwidth.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] Another major difference between CUBIC and many earlier TCP algorithms is that it does not rely on the cadence of RTTs to increase the window size.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] CUBIC's window size is dependent only on the last congestion event.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] With earlier algorithms like TCP New Reno, flows with very short round-trip delay times (RTTs) will receive ACKs faster and therefore have their congestion windows grow faster than other flows with longer RTTs.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] CUBIC allows for more fairness between flows since the window growth is independent of RTT.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] This RTT-independence is particularly important in modern data centers and cloud environments where flows may traverse paths with vastly different round-trip times.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] Studies have shown that in networks with mixed RTT flows, CUBIC achieves up to 3-5 times better fairness compared to traditional loss-based algorithms like Reno.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] The RTT-fairness property makes CUBIC especially suitable for Content Delivery Networks (CDNs) and distributed systems where servers at different geographical locations communicate with clients simultaneously.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] CUBIC increases its window to be real-time dependent, not RTT dependent like BIC.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] The calculation for cwnd (congestion window) is simpler than BIC, too.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] Apart from window based algorithms like Cubic, there are rate based algorithms (including TCP BBR from Google) that works differently using "sending rate" instead of the window.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] Unlike CUBIC, which relies primarily on packet loss as a congestion signal, BBR uses a model-based approach that estimates the available bandwidth and minimum RTT of the network path.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] BBR operates by cycling through four states: STARTUP, DRAIN, PROBE_BW, and PROBE_RTT, continuously measuring and adapting to network conditions.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] The fundamental difference in approach means that BBR can achieve higher throughput in networks with shallow buffers or where random packet loss occurs (such as wireless networks), as it doesn't interpret all losses as congestion signals.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/cubic-tcp] However, studies have shown that when BBR flows compete with CUBIC flows, BBR can be more aggressive and may dominate bandwidth allocation.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] The **additive-increase/multiplicative-decrease** (**AIMD**) algorithm is a feedback control algorithm best known for its use in TCP congestion control.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] AIMD combines linear growth of the congestion window when there is no congestion with an exponential reduction when congestion is detected.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] Multiple flows using AIMD congestion control will eventually converge to an equal usage of a shared link.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] The related schemes of multiplicative-increase/multiplicative-decrease (MIMD) and additive-increase/additive-decrease (AIAD) do not reach stability.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] The approach taken is to increase the transmission rate (window size), probing for usable bandwidth, until loss occurs.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] The policy of additive increase may, for instance, increase the congestion window by a fixed amount every round-trip time.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] When congestion is detected, the transmitter decreases the transmission rate by a multiplicative factor; for example, cut the congestion window in half after loss.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] The result is a saw-tooth behavior that represents the process of bandwidth probing.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] AIMD requires a binary congestion signal.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] Most frequently, packet loss serves as the signal; the multiplicative decrease is triggered when a timeout or an acknowledgement message indicates a packet lost.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] It is also possible for in-network switches/routers to mark congestion (without discarding packets) as in Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN).
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] Let $w(t)$ be the congestion window size indicating the amount of data in flight during time slot t , a ( $a>0$ ) be the additive increase parameter, and b ( $0<b<1$ ) be the multiplicative decrease factor.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] In TCP, after slow start, the additive increase parameter a is typically one MSS (maximum segment size) per round-trip time, and the multiplicative decrease factor b is typically 1/2.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/multiplicative-decrease] AIMD has been found to be utilized by diverse biological systems, including maintaining cell-size homeostasis and for synaptic learning and adaptation in neural circuits.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) uses one of several congestion control algorithms that include various aspects of an additive increase/multiplicative decrease (AIMD) scheme, along with other schemes including slow start and a congestion window (CWND), to achieve congestion avoidance.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The **TCP congestion-avoidance algorithm** is the primary basis for congestion control in the Internet.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Per the end-to-end principle, congestion control is largely a function of internet hosts, not the network itself.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] There are several variations and versions of the algorithm implemented in protocol stacks of operating systems of computers that connect to the Internet.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] To avoid congestive collapse, TCP uses a multi-faceted congestion-control strategy.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] For each connection, TCP maintains a CWND, limiting the total number of unacknowledged packets that may be in transit end-to-end.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] This is somewhat analogous to TCP's sliding window used for flow control.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The additive increase/multiplicative decrease (AIMD) algorithm is a closed-loop control algorithm.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] AIMD combines linear growth of the congestion window with an exponential reduction when congestion occurs.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Multiple flows using AIMD congestion control will eventually converge to use equal amounts of a contended link.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] This is the algorithm that is described in RFC 5681 for the *congestion avoidance* state.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] In TCP, the **congestion window** (CWND) is one of the factors that determines the number of bytes that can be sent out at any time.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The congestion window is maintained by the sender and is a means of preventing *a link* between the sender and the receiver from becoming overloaded with too much traffic.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] This should not be confused with the sliding window maintained by the sender, which exists to prevent *the receiver* from becoming overloaded.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The congestion window is calculated by estimating how much congestion there is on the link.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] When a connection is set up, the congestion window, a value maintained independently at each host, is set to a small multiple of the **maximum segment size** (**MSS**) allowed on that connection.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Further variance in the congestion window is dictated by an additive increase/multiplicative decrease (AIMD) approach.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] This means that if all segments are received and the acknowledgments reach the sender on time, some constant is added to the window size.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] A system administrator may adjust the maximum window size limit or adjust the constant added during additive increase, as part of TCP tuning.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The flow of data over a TCP connection is also controlled by the use of the *receive window* advertised by the receiver.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] A sender can send data less than its own congestion window and the *receive window*.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Slow start, defined by RFC 5681, is part of the congestion control strategy used by TCP in conjunction with other algorithms to avoid sending more data than the network is capable of forwarding, that is, to avoid causing network congestion.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Slow start begins initially with a congestion window size (CWND) of 1, 2, 4 or 10 MSS.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The value for the congestion window size can be increased by 1 MSS with each acknowledgment (ACK) received, effectively doubling the window size each RTT.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] If the CWND reaches *ssthresh*, TCP switches to the congestion avoidance algorithm.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It should be increased by up to 1 MSS for each RTT.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] A common formula is that *each new ACK* increases the CWND by *MSS * MSS / CWND.* It increases almost linearly and provides an acceptable approximation.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] If a loss event occurs, TCP assumes that it is due to network congestion and takes steps to reduce the offered load on the network.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] These measures depend on the exact TCP congestion avoidance algorithm used.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] When a TCP sender detects segment loss using the retransmission timer and the given segment has not yet been resent, the value of *ssthresh* must be set to no more than half of the amount of data that has been sent but not yet cumulatively acknowledged or *2 * MSS*, whichever value is greater.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] and slow start begins again from its initial CWND.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] and as the new value for CWND, thus skipping slow start and going directly to the congestion avoidance algorithm.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Slow start assumes that unacknowledged segments are due to network congestion.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] While this is an acceptable assumption for many networks, segments may be lost for other reasons, such as poor data link layer transmission quality.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Thus, slow start can perform poorly in situations with poor reception, such as wireless networks.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The slow start protocol also performs badly for short-lived connections.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Older web browsers would create many consecutive short-lived connections to the web server, and would open and close the connection for each file requested.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] This kept most connections in the slow start mode, which resulted in poor response time.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] To avoid this problem, modern browsers either open multiple connections simultaneously or reuse one connection for all files requested from a particular web server.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Connections, however, cannot be reused for the multiple third-party servers used by websites to implement web advertising, sharing features of social networking services, and counter scripts of web analytics.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] When a sender receives three duplicate acknowledgments, it can be reasonably confident that the segment carrying the data that followed the last in-order byte specified in the acknowledgment was lost.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] A sender with fast retransmit will then retransmit this packet immediately without waiting for its timeout.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] On receipt of the retransmitted segment, the receiver can acknowledge the last in-order byte of data received.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] In the above example, this would acknowledge to the end of the payload of the fifth packet.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] There is no need to acknowledge intermediate packets since TCP uses cumulative acknowledgments by default.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The names Reno and Tahoe are the names of releases of the BSD UNIX operating system, and were used to refer to the congestion control algorithms (CCAs) at least as early a 1996 paper by Kevin Fall and Sally Floyd.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Tahoe and Reno algorithms were retrospectively named after the versions or flavors of the 4.3BSD operating system in which each first appeared (which were themselves named after Lake Tahoe and the nearby city of Reno, Nevada).
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The Tahoe algorithm first appeared in 4.3BSD-Tahoe (which was made to support the CCI Power 6/32 "Tahoe" minicomputer), and was later made available to non-AT&T licensees as part of the 4.3BSD Networking Release 1; this ensured its wide distribution and implementation.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Improvements were made in 4.3BSD-Reno and subsequently released to the public as Networking Release 2 and later 4.4BSD-Lite.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] In both Tahoe and Reno, if an ACK times out (RTO timeout), slow start is used, and both algorithms reduce the congestion window to 1 MSS.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] TCP New Reno, defined by RFC 6582 (which obsolesces previous definitions in RFC 3782 and RFC 2582), improves retransmission during the fast-recovery phase of TCP Reno.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] During fast recovery, to keep the transmit window full, for every duplicate ACK that is returned, a new unsent packet from the end of the congestion window is sent.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The difference from Reno is that New Reno does not halve ssthresh immediately, which may reduce the window too much if multiple packet losses occur.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It does not exit fast-recovery and reset ssthresh until it acknowledges all of the data.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It uses a variable called *recover* to record how much data needs to be recovered.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] After a retransmit timeout, it records the highest sequence number transmitted in the recover variable and exits the fast recovery procedure.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] If this sequence number is acknowledged, TCP returns to the congestion avoidance state.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] A problem occurs with New Reno when there are no packet losses, but instead, packets are reordered by more than 3 packet sequence numbers.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] In this case, New Reno mistakenly enters fast recovery.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] When the reordered packet is delivered, duplicate and needless retransmissions are immediately sent.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] New Reno performs as well as SACK at low packet error rates and substantially outperforms Reno at high error rates.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Until the mid-1990s, all of TCP's set timeouts and measured round-trip delays were based upon only the last transmitted packet in the transmit buffer.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] University of Arizona researchers Larry Peterson and Lawrence Brakmo introduced TCP Vegas, in which timeouts were set and round-trip delays were measured for every packet in the transmit buffer.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] In addition, TCP Vegas uses additive increases in the congestion window.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] In a 2012 comparison study of various TCP CCAs, TCP Vegas appeared to be the smoothest, followed by TCP CUBIC.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Vegas was not widely deployed outside Peterson's laboratory but was selected as the default congestion control method for DD-WRT firmware v24 SP2.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Hybla aims to eliminate penalties to TCP connections that use high-latency terrestrial or satellite radio links.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Hybla improvements are based on analytical evaluation of the congestion window dynamics.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Binary Increase Congestion control (BIC) is a TCP implementation with an optimized CCA for high-speed networks with high latency, known as long fat networks (LFNs).
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] BIC is used by default in Linux kernels 2.6.8 through 2.6.18.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] CUBIC is a less aggressive and more systematic derivative of BIC, in which the window is a cubic function of time since the last congestion event, with the inflection point set to the window prior to the event.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] CUBIC is used by default in Linux kernels since version 2.6.19.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Agile-SD is a Linux-based CCA that is designed for the real Linux kernel.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It has been evaluated by comparing its performance to Compound TCP (the default CCA in MS Windows) and CUBIC (the default of Linux) using the NS-2 simulator.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It improves the total performance up to 55% in terms of average throughput.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Westwood+ is a sender-only modification of TCP Reno that optimizes the performance of TCP congestion control over both wired and wireless networks.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Westwood+ is based on end-to-end bandwidth estimation to set the congestion window and slow-start threshold after a congestion episode, that is, after three duplicate acknowledgments or a timeout.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The bandwidth is estimated by averaging the rate of returning acknowledgment packets.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] In contrast with TCP Reno, which blindly halves the congestion window after three duplicate ACKs, TCP Westwood+ adaptively sets a slow-start threshold and a congestion window that takes into account an estimate of bandwidth available at the time congestion is experienced.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Compared to Reno and New Reno, Westwood+ significantly increases throughput over wireless links and improves fairness in wired networks.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Compound TCP is a Microsoft implementation of TCP that maintains two different congestion windows simultaneously, with the goal of achieving good performance on LFNs while not impairing fairness.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It has been widely deployed in Windows versions since Microsoft Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008 and has been ported to older Microsoft Windows versions as well as Linux.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Proportional Rate Reduction (PRR) is an algorithm designed to improve the accuracy of data sent during recovery.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The algorithm ensures that the window size after recovery is as close as possible to the slow start threshold.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] In tests performed by Google, PRR resulted in a 3–10% reduction in average latency and recovery timeouts were reduced by 5%.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] PRR is available in Linux kernels since version 3.2.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Bottleneck Bandwidth and Round-trip propagation time (BBR) is a CCA developed at Google in 2016.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] While most CCAs are loss-based, in that they rely on packet loss to detect congestion and lower rates of transmission, BBR, like TCP Vegas, is model-based.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The algorithm uses the maximum bandwidth and round-trip time at which the network delivered the most recent flight of outbound data packets to build a model of the network.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Each cumulative or selective acknowledgment of packet delivery produces a rate sample that records the amount of data delivered over the time interval between the transmission of a data packet and the acknowledgment of that packet.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] When implemented at YouTube, BBRv1 yielded an average of 4% higher network throughput and up to 14% in some countries.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] BBR has been available for Linux TCP since Linux 4.9.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] BBR version 1 (BBRv1) fairness to non-BBR streams is disputed.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] While Google's presentation shows BBRv1 co-existing well with CUBIC, researchers like Geoff Huston and Hock, Bless and Zitterbart found it unfair to other streams and not scalable.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Hock et al. also found "some severe inherent issues such as increased queuing delays, unfairness, and massive packet loss" in the BBR implementation of Linux 4.9.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] (authors of C2TCP) show that BBRv1 doesn't perform well in dynamic environments such as cellular networks.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] They have also shown that BBR has an unfairness issue.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] For instance, when a CUBIC flow (which is the default TCP implementation in Linux, Android, and MacOS) coexists with a BBR flow in the network, the BBR flow can dominate the CUBIC flow and get the whole link bandwidth from it (see figure 18 in).
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Version 2 attempts to deal with the issue of unfairness when operating alongside loss-based congestion management such as CUBIC.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] In BBRv2 the model used by BBRv1 is augmented to include information about packet loss and information from Explicit Congestion Notification (ECN).
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Whilst BBRv2 may at times have lower throughput than BBRv1 it is generally considered to have better goodput.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Windows 11, version 24H2 and Windows Server 2025 had support for BBRv2, but may not enable it by default.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Version 3 (BBRv3) fixes two bugs in BBRv2 (premature end of bandwidth probing, bandwidth convergence) and performs some performance tuning.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] There is also a variant, termed BBR.Swift, optimized for datacenter-internal links: it uses network_RTT (excluding receiver delay) as the main congestion control signal.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Cellular Controlled Delay TCP (C2TCP) was motivated by the lack of a flexible end-to-end TCP approach that can satisfy various QoS requirements for different applications without requiring any changes in the network devices.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] C2TCP aims to satisfy ultra-low latency and high-bandwidth requirements of applications such as virtual reality, video conferencing, online gaming, vehicular communication systems, etc. in a highly dynamic environment such as current LTE and future 5G cellular networks.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] C2TCP works as an add-on on top of loss-based TCP (e.g., Reno, NewReno, CUBIC, BIC, ...), it is only required to be installed on the server side and makes the average delay of packets bounded to the desired delays set by the applications.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Researchers at NYU showed that C2TCP outperforms the delay and delay-variation performance of various state-of-the-art TCP schemes.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] For instance, they showed that compared to BBR, CUBIC, and Westwood on average, C2TCP decreases the average delay of packets by about 250%, 900%, and 700%, respectively on various cellular network environments.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Elastic-TCP was proposed in February 2019 to increase bandwidth utilization over high-BDP networks in support of cloud computing.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It is a Linux-based CCA that is designed for the Linux kernel.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It is a receiver-side algorithm that employs a loss-delay-based approach using a novel mechanism called a window-correlated weighting function (WWF).
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It has a high level of elasticity to deal with different network characteristics without the need for human tuning.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It has been evaluated by comparing its performance to Compound TCP (the default CCA in MS Windows), CUBIC (the default for Linux) and TCP-BBR (the default of Linux 4.9 used by Google) using the NS-2 simulator and testbed.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Elastic-TCP significantly improves the total performance in terms of average throughput, loss ratio, and delay.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Soheil Abbasloo et al. proposed NATCP (Network-Assisted TCP), a controversial TCP design targeting multi-access edge computing (MEC).
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The key idea of NATCP is that if the characteristics of the network were known beforehand, TCP would have been designed differently.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Therefore, NATCP employs the available features and properties in the current MEC-based cellular architectures to push the performance of TCP close to the optimal performance.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] NATCP uses out-of-band feedback from the network to the servers located nearby.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The feedback from the network, which includes the capacity of the cellular access link and the minimum RTT of the network, guides the servers to adjust their sending rates.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] As preliminary results show, NATCP outperforms the state-of-the-art TCP schemes.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] TCP New Reno was the most commonly implemented algorithm, SACK support is very common and is an extension to Reno/New Reno.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Most others are competing proposals that still need evaluation.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Starting with 2.6.8 the Linux kernel switched the default implementation from New Reno to BIC.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] The default implementation was again changed to CUBIC in the 2.6.19 version.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] FreeBSD from version 14.X onwards also uses CUBIC as the default algorithm.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] However, FreeBSD supports a number of other choices.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] When the per-flow product of bandwidth and latency increases, regardless of the queuing scheme, TCP becomes inefficient and prone to instability.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] This becomes increasingly important as the Internet evolves to incorporate very high-bandwidth optical links.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] TCP Interactive (iTCP) allows applications to subscribe to TCP events and respond accordingly, enabling various functional extensions to TCP from outside TCP layer.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Most TCP congestion schemes work internally. iTCP additionally enables advanced applications to directly participate in congestion control, such as to control the source generation rate.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Zeta-TCP detects congestion from both latency and loss rate measures.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] To maximize the goodput, Zeta-TCP applies different congestion window backoff strategies based on the likelihood of congestion.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] It also has other improvements to accurately detect packet losses, avoiding retransmission timeout, and accelerate and control the inbound (download) traffic.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] CCAs may be classified in relation to network awareness, meaning the extent to which these algorithms are aware of the state of the network.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] This consist of three primary categories: black box, grey box, and green box.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Black box algorithms offer blind methods of congestion control.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] They operate only on the binary feedback received upon congestion and do not assume any knowledge concerning the state of the networks which they manage.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Grey box algorithms use time-based measurements, such as RTT variation and rate of packet arrival, in order to obtain measurements and estimations of bandwidth, flow contention, and other knowledge of network conditions.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-congestion-control] Green box algorithms offer bimodal methods of congestion control that measure the fair share of total bandwidth that should be allocated for each flow, at any point, during the system's execution.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] TCP Vegas was one of the first delay-based congestion control algorithms, representing a paradigm shift from traditional loss-based approaches.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] Unlike TCP Reno which waits for packet loss to indicate congestion, Vegas monitors changes in round-trip time to proactively detect network congestion before buffers overflow and packets are dropped.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] This approach allows Vegas to maintain smaller queue sizes and achieve lower latency compared to loss-based algorithms.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] TCP Vegas detects congestion at an incipient stage based on increasing Round-Trip Time (RTT) values of the packets in the connection unlike other flavors such as Reno, New Reno, etc., which detect congestion only after it has actually happened via packet loss.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] The algorithm depends heavily on accurate calculation of the Base RTT value.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] If it is too small then throughput of the connection will be less than the bandwidth available while if the value is too large then it will overrun the connection.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] A lot of research is going on regarding the fairness provided by the linear increase/decrease mechanism for congestion control in Vegas.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] One interesting caveat is when Vegas is inter-operated with other versions like Reno.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] In this case, performance of Vegas degrades because Vegas reduces its sending rate before Reno, as it detects congestion early and hence gives greater bandwidth to co-existing TCP Reno flows.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] This unfairness issue arises because Vegas interprets the increased queuing delay caused by aggressive Reno flows as congestion and backs off, while Reno continues to increase its window until packet loss occurs.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] TCP Vegas is one of several *flavors* of TCP congestion avoidance algorithms.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] It is one of a series of efforts at TCP tuning that adapt congestion control and system behaviors to new challenges faced by increases in available bandwidth in Internet components on networks like Internet2.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] TCP Vegas has been implemented in the Linux kernel, in FreeBSD, in Solaris.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] Despite its implementation in major operating systems, TCP Vegas has seen limited deployment in production environments.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] Linux included Vegas support starting with kernel 2.4.13 in 2001, where it can be enabled through the sysctl interface.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] However, due to the fairness issues when competing with loss-based algorithms and the need for accurate RTT measurements, Vegas is rarely enabled by default.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] The algorithm has found more success in controlled environments such as data centers and private networks where all hosts can use the same congestion control algorithm.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] Some modern algorithms, including TCP BBR developed by Google, have drawn inspiration from Vegas's delay-based approach while attempting to address its shortcomings.
[src:tcp-congestion-control/tcp-vegas] Research continues on hybrid approaches that combine Vegas's proactive congestion detection with mechanisms to ensure fair competition with loss-based algorithms.
